A 'Quercus fusiformis' is a species of oak tree native to the southern United States. 
It can grow up to 40 feet tall with a trunk diameter of up to 2 feet. 
Its leaves are dark green and glossy with a leathery texture, and they are obovate or oblong in shape. 
The bark of the 'Quercus fusiformis' is rough and furrowed, which can be dark gray or brown in color. 
The acorns of the tree are up to an inch long, and they have distinctive caps which can cover up to a third of the acorn. 
The wood of the 'Quercus fusiformis' is dense and heavy, making it useful for furniture and flooring. 
It is commonly found in areas such as woodlands, forests, and parks in the southern states of the USA.
